See also: Danser

Afrikaans

[edit]

Etymology

[edit]

From Dutch danser, from Middle Dutch danser. Equivalent to dans +‎ -er.

Pronunciation

[edit]
  • Audio:(file)

Noun

[edit]

danser (plural dansers)

  1. dancer

Danish

[edit]

Alternative forms

[edit]
  • dandser (obsolete)

Noun

[edit]

danser c (singular definite danseren, plural indefinite dansere)

  1. a dancer

Declension

[edit]
Declension of danser
common
gender 		singular plural
indefinite definite indefinite definite
nominative danser danseren dansere danserne
genitive dansers danserens danseres dansernes

Related terms

[edit]
  • danserinde
  • danserske

Verb

[edit]

danser

  1. present of danse

Dutch

[edit]

Etymology

[edit]

From Middle Dutch danser. Equivalent to dansen +‎ -er.

Pronunciation

[edit]
  • IPA(key): /ˈdɑnsər/
  • Audio:(file)
  • Hyphenation: dan‧ser

Noun

[edit]

danser m (plural dansers, diminutive dansertje n, feminine danseres)

  1. dancer, person who dances

Derived terms

[edit]
  • koorddanser

Descendants

[edit]
  • Afrikaans: danser

Anagrams

[edit]
  • anders, Sander

French

[edit]

Etymology

[edit]

From Old French dancier, from Vulgar Latin *dantiāre. Displaced the older Old French baller.

Pronunciation

[edit]
  • IPA(key): /dɑ̃.se/
  • Audio:(file)
  • Audio (France (Vosges)):(file)
  • Audio (France (Lyon)):(file)
  • Audio (France (Somain)):(file)

Verb

[edit]

danser

  1. (ambitransitive) to dance

Derived terms

[edit]
  • absent le chat, les souris dansent
  • quand le chat n'est pas là, les souris dansent
  • le chat parti, les souris dansent
  • ne pas savoir sur quel pied danser

Related terms

[edit]
  • danse
  • danseur, danseuse

[edit]

  • → Romanian: dansa

Norman

[edit]

Etymology

[edit]

From Old French dancier (“to dance”).

Pronunciation

[edit]
  • Audio (Jersey):(file)

Verb

[edit]

danser (gerund dans'sie)

  1. (Jersey) to dance

Noun

  1. a dancer
